00:14:06.660 --> 00:14:08.710
because Sam said that it was
a really application.

00:14:08.710 --> 00:14:11.610
And vice versa, if Sam gives
it a negative review, then

00:14:11.610 --> 00:14:15.250
obviously, I would take that
data point in too.

00:14:15.250 --> 00:14:17.080
I would basically trust that
interview more than an

00:14:17.080 --> 00:14:17.520
anonymous review.

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:22.230
So for example, if I'm signed
into Amazon, then I have a lot

00:14:22.230 --> 00:14:24.250
of reviews, with a lot of
ratings, and I'm not really

00:14:24.250 --> 00:14:25.830
sure whether--

00:14:25.830 --> 00:14:26.720
I don't know these people.

00:14:26.720 --> 00:14:30.450
So if I can see Sam reviewing
something, I have much more

00:14:30.450 --> 00:14:32.550
confidence in that review
then if it's

00:14:32.550 --> 00:14:34.380
just some random person.

00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:35.730
Even if those reviews
are good.

00:14:35.730 --> 00:14:37.240
It's just a human thing.

00:14:37.240 --> 00:14:39.600
And again, when we talk about
social here, it's really

00:14:39.600 --> 00:14:43.780
important to think of this as
a human experience, because

00:14:43.780 --> 00:14:46.090
social should not be
some feature set.

00:14:46.090 --> 00:14:47.690
Like I mentioned three
features--

00:14:47.690 --> 00:14:51.400
sign-in, personalization,
and sharing.

00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:54.840
Social is just not a composite
of these features, social is

00:14:54.840 --> 00:14:56.500
something that we
do as humans.

00:14:56.500 --> 00:15:00.390
And these features are trying
to enhance what we would

00:15:00.390 --> 00:15:02.470
normally do anyway as people.

00:15:02.470 --> 00:15:05.630
So that's, I think, another
kind of meta concept.

00:15:05.630 --> 00:15:07.230
But I think it's really
important to now.

00:15:07.230 --> 00:15:09.970
And that's why we talked about
making users feel good about

00:15:09.970 --> 00:15:12.460
the choice they've
made, and so on.

